<p>Here is how to use the “\(ac\)” method to factor a trinomial.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1 -</strong> Is there a greatest common factor?</p>
<p> \(10y^2-55y+70\)<br/>
    Yes. The GCF is 5.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2 -</strong> Factor it.</p>
<p> \(5(2y^2-11y+14)\)</p>
<p><strong>Step 3 - </strong>The trinomial inside the parentheses has a leading coefficient that is not \(1\).</p>
<p> \(\begin{array}{c}{\style{color:red}a}{\style{color:red}x}^{\style{color:red}2}+{\style{color:red}b}{\style{color:red}x}+{\style{color:red}c}\\5(2y^2-11y+14)\end{array}\) </p>
<p>Find the product \(ac\).<br/>
    \(ac=28\)</p>
<p><strong>Step 4 - </strong>Find two numbers that multiply to \(ac\) and add to \(b\).</p>
<p> \((-4)(-7)=28\)<br/>
    \(-4+(-7)=-11\)</p>
<p><strong>Step 5 - </strong>Split the middle term.</p>
<p><img alt="An equation, 5(2y squared – 11y + 14), splits into 5(2y squared – 7y – 4y + 14), with arrows showing the transformation and brackets highlighting the grouped terms –7y and –4y." src="https://k12.openstax.org/contents/raise/resources/2bd20fbcb7c846a9536d0ae1464d5c3bde7ccaea"/><br/>
</p>
<p><strong>Step 6 -</strong> Factor the trinomial by grouping.</p>
<p> \(5(y(2y-7)-2(2y-7))\)<br/>
    \(5(y-2)(2y-7)\)</p>
<p><strong>Step 7 -</strong> Check by multiplying all three factors.</p>
