<h4>Factoring Trinomials Using Substitution</h4>
<p>Sometimes a trinomial does not appear to be in the \(ax^2 + bx + c\) form. However, we can often make a thoughtful substitution that will allow us to make it fit the \(ax^2 + bx + c\) form. This is called factoring by substitution. It is standard to use \(u\) for the substitution.</p>
<p>In the form \(ax^2 + bx + c\), the middle term has a variable, \(x\), and its square, \(x^2\), is the variable part of the first term. Look for this relationship as you try to find a substitution.</p>
<p><strong>Example 2</strong></p>
<p>Factor by substitution: \(x^4 − 4x^2 − 5\).</p>
<p>The variable part of the middle term is \(x^2\), and its square, \(x^4\), is the variable part of the first term. (We know \((x^2)^2 = x^4)\). If we let \(u = x^2\), we can put our trinomial in the \(ax^2 + bx + c\) form we need to factor it.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1 - </strong>Rewrite the trinomial to prepare for the substitution.</p>
<p> \(({\style{color:red}x}^{\style{color:red}2})^2-4({\style{color:red}x}^{\style{color:red}2})-5\)</p>
<p><strong>Step 2 -</strong> Let \(u=x^2\) and substitute.</p>
<p> \({\style{color:red}u}^2-4{\style{color:red}u}-5\) </p>
<p><strong>Step 3 - </strong>Factor the trinomial.</p>
<p> \((u +1)(u-5)\)</p>
<p><strong>Step 4 -</strong> Replace \(u\) with \(x^2\).</p>
<p> \(({\style{color:red}x}^{\style{color:red}2}+1)({\style{color:red}x}^{\style{color:red}2}-5)\) </p>
<p><strong>Step 5 - </strong>Check:</p>
